  <mainDescription>The project management plan is the formal document that lays out how a project is to be managed, executed and controlled.&#xD;
Throughout the project, it is continually refined, revised and updated.</mainDescription>
  <keyConsiderations>This document belongs to the whole project team. The project manager is the final editor and sometime author of the project&#xD;
management plan.</keyConsiderations>
  <impactOfNotHaving>Project chaos, increased process risks and possible project failure.</impactOfNotHaving>
  <reasonsForNotNeeding>The project management plan should be tailored to risk. The lower the risk the fewer process restrictions. Some low risk&#xD;
project may use very simple plans.</reasonsForNotNeeding>
  <briefOutline>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The project management plan typically consists of:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        3 baselines; Cost, Schedule and Scope&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        10 management plans; requirements, scope, cost, quality, risk, change, configuration, schedule, procurement, and&#xD;
        communications&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        1 human resource plan&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></briefOutline>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
